e process by which consumers’ access to goods and services was liberalized and deregulated in Canada in the second half of the twentieth century. Michael Dawson’s engagingly written and detailed exploration of the debates amongst everyday citizens and politicians regarding the pros and cons of expanding shopping opportunities, challenges the assumption of inevitability surrounding Canada’s emergence as a consumer society. The expansion of store hours was a highly contested and contingent development that pitted employees, owners and regulators against one another. Dawson’s nuanced analysis of archival and newspaper sources reveals the strains that modern capitalism imparted upon the accepted and established rhythms of daily life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aConsumer behaviorzBritish ColumbiazVancouverxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumer behaviorzBritish ColumbiazVictoriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumption (Economics)zBritish ColumbiazVancouverxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumption (Economics)zBritish ColumbiazVictoriaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751487740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487514877423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487514877.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK